40|$|European Company Laws: A Comparative Approach is a {{compilation}} of ten essays by various authors on the jurisprudence of corporate control within Europe. The book focuses on the <b>company</b> <b>laws</b> within the various member states, somewhat {{to the exclusion of}} the emerging EC-level corporate laws. Yet while European <b>Company</b> <b>Laws</b> concerns itself with member states 2 ̆ 7 internal <b>company</b> <b>laws,</b> the book 2 ̆ 7 s goal is much loftier than merely compiling the European states 2 ̆ 7 corporate statutes into some sort of practitioners 2 ̆ 7 guide. Rather, European <b>Company</b> <b>Laws</b> attempts to divine jurisprudential truths about the regulation of power within the European company by examining the European company from different substantive law perspectives. Each of the book 2 ̆ 7 s nine substantive chapters takes a different approach toward the same destination: Divining the nature of control within the European enterprise...|$|R
